Guys, check this out. A post from ex-IUTian

Assalamualaikum,

If anyone considering to apply for a CS PhD program in USA for the upcoming fall 2021 session, you can have a look at George Mason University. Recently, GMU has taken many initiatives to expand the CS department and brand it as the School of Computing eventually. Within Fall 21, 8 tenure track assistant professors and 2 professors are joining and some of them are already looking for students. Here is the full list: ([https://cs.gmu.edu/blog/incoming-cs-faculty-share-secrets-to-success-for-students/](https://cs.gmu.edu/blog/incoming-cs-faculty-share-secrets-to-success-for-students/)) and you can have a look into their works. You will find professors working in areas like NLP, vision, ML, DATA SCIENCE, HPC, SWE, BIOINFORMATICS, ROBOTICS, IOT, AUTONOMOUS VEHICLE, NETWORKING, CYBERSECURITY, SYSTEM ENGINEERING

Some facts about GMU are:

#Here you will get a big iutian community. Currently Junayed Mahmud (CSE 12), Mahbubul Alam Palash (CSE 12), Mahfuz Alam (CSE 14), Taseef Rahman (EEE 12) and me (CSE 12) are doing our phd in GMU CS dept. Our Arif sir from CIT 07 is in the process of finishing his phd. Besides, Raihan Islam Arnob (CSE 12) will join from Fall 20 and another one will start from spring 21.

#Not necessarily you have to contact any professor before applying or before getting admission as the admission process is central. You will get guaranteed 2 years GTA position and I saw people getting GTA offers from the dept after completing this 2-year position because of the demand/vacancy and large undergraduate enrolment.

#Here you will get the time to figure out with whom you want to work eventually. As the department is there to support you for more or less 3 years at least, changing your supervisor in the meantime is not a big deal here.

#Besides CS dept, there are IT dept and bioengineering dept where you can find professors to work with being a CS PhD student. Because many professors from these depts do interdisciplinary and cs related research and they need students.

#Fairfax is a very safe, nice but costly city to live in. So if you are thinking of saving large or something like having a cost of living like Texas for eg, this might not be the right place for you. No issue if you are single but most of the students who live with their spouses here, have to share their rent with another person because of this high living cost. You won't face issues like racism or gun violence here. Besides, you will find all kinds of ethnic and halal food here without having any issue. Also, this location is very close to Washington DC.

#From last 2 years data, you should get admission with a moderate profile here. The good thing is, we don't see any hard GRE/CGPA cutoff score usually here. For example, I got admission with a GRE verbal score of 144, IELTS speaking score of 6 and no publication at fall 19. Considering the current trend, I assume if you have something like 1) GRE 308/+ and CGPA 3.55/+  2) GRE 314/+ AND CGPA 3.05/+ with some work experience you have a chance of getting admission. And here admission means guaranteed funding. These are just some of my assumptions. The admission committee tries to look at a profile holistically I believe. 
#If you did your undergraduate from other depts like eee/mce and want to move into CS, you can give it a shot. Taseef Rahman is from EEE 12 and currently doing his PhD in cs here.

#I want to encourage current 4th-year students to take the GRE and just apply this year if you have intentions to go for HSA. Mahfuz Alam from CSE'14 applied just after his graduation and started his PhD within 8 months. I think this is a nice approach and will save you from wasting time. I am saying this because I know, there are students who have the easy capability to try this but just don't like to start early because of some kind of hesitation/confusion/laziness. In reality, this process of application doesn't need that amount of time which it seems at that stage.

My apology for a long post with grammatical errors. Anyone can knock me/others from IUT-GMU if you need any info. Happy to help.
